ship and romantic relationships, and how it differs from place to place. Hruschka argues that friendship is a special form of reciprocal altruism based not on tit-for-tat accounting or forward-looking rationality, but rather on mutual goodwill that is built up along the way in human relationships.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFriendshipxSocial aspects. 0aHuman behavior. 0aInterpersonal relations. 0aKinship. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aaffect theory.  aafrica.  aaltruism.  aanimal friendships.  aanthropology.  abiocultural anthropology.  achina.  acompanionship.  acooperation.  acultural anthropology.  aemotions.  aethnography.  aevolution.  aevolutionary biology.  afamily relationships.  afear.  afriendship.  agenerosity.  agermany.  agoodwill.  ahuman behavior.  aiceland.  aimaginary friends.  akinship.  amaasai.  anonfiction.  aplatonic relationships.  apsychology.  areciprocal altruism.  areciprocity.  arelationships.  areputation.  aromantic relationships.  arussia.  ascience.  ashame.  asocial networks.  asociety.  atrust.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026546240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094788740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947887423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520947887/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY